The paper deals with clustering algorithms, which are typically studied in the sub-categories of computer science related to data structures (cs.DS), machine learning (cs.LG), data mining (cs.DM), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and social and information networks (cs.SI). Specifically, the paper introduces a new type of clustering algorithm called local correlation clustering, which has implications for distributed and streaming clustering algorithms, constant-time estimators and testers for cluster edit distance, and property-preserving parallel reconstruction algorithms for clusterability. These topics are relevant to all of the aforementioned sub-categories, hence the paper could potentially be classified under any of them. However, given that the paper focuses on the theoretical aspects of clustering algorithms and their computational complexity, it is most likely to be classified under cs.DS and cs.LG, followed by cs.DM, cs.AI, and cs.SI.
